[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'What happens in the final seconds before a plane crash? Well, the blackbox recorder was invented to answer that question, but then it crept into cars. It started small. Blackboxes recorded crash data, speeds, and braking. We shared all this information in the name of safety and cheaper insurance rates.'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'But then the data mining grew. Cars got SIM cards, microphones, and even cameras. And the data they collected changed. It was no longer just about safety, but where did you go yesterday? How fast were you going? Did you break'

[00:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'too hard? Who were you with? Who did you call? What did you say? And can we sell this information to anybody else? The blackbox was invented to prevent airline disasters. But the smart car turned that into a business model. Today, I\'m going'

[00:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'to show you how your car spies on you, from the smallest ways to the most alarming, and what you can do to stop it. Inside a car, there can be up to 150 small computers called electronic control units. They\'re built into'

[00:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'different parts of the car, including the door, the boot, the engine, the wheels, and more. And it makes sense. Some cars generate nearly 25 gigabytes of data per hour, collecting information from more than 100 different data'

[01:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'points. &gt;&gt; This data really comes from two sources. Uh one are the sensors in the cars and then from the devices you connect such as your cell phone. Um and so this data migrates from your personal device into the car.'

[01:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; These can include embedded features, geoloccation and navigation, biometrics, and more. This is not just a car that has a computer inside it. It\'s more a computer that happens to have wheels. But it\'s not just data about the car. It\'s data about you. Some cars, like'

[01:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'BMWs, Hyundai\'s, and Teslas, collect fingerprints and facial images to unlock the car or for driver recognition. Nearly all cars now collect voice recordings for voice assistance. Medical information for emergency assistance'

[01:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'services, including everything from the driver\'s heart rate to crash severity data, financial details for in-car purchases, passwords, your home address, and connected features like your home garage door code. But it\'s not just the'

[01:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'drivers they spy on. Modern vehicles sense the entire world around them and inside them. &gt;&gt; If you look at your passenger for a moment, an alarm sounds and a message pops up saying, "Keep your eyes on the road."'

[02:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; According to Reuters, between 2019 and 2022, Tesla employees shared private footage taken from customers cars cameras. Governments have noticed this, too. Reportedly, Tesla vehicles have been restricted from entering sensitive government and military spaces in China'

[02:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'because of concerns of sensors and cameras collecting sensitive data. So, if a whole national government is worried about what cars can see, maybe we as individuals should be, too. Once all the data is collected, where does it'

[02:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'go? In 2024, a Chevy Volt driver named Mike Tana requested the information his car collected on it and received a behavioral report from OnStar, his onboard telematics program. There was something strange about what he saw.'

[02:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'Every day, at almost the exact same time, something stood out. A near miss collision, small object. Every day, same time, same place. It\'s weird until you realize that Mike had cats who loved him'

[02:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'very much. Every day when he would drive home, his cats would get excited and run out in front of the car. A near miss collision with his cats in his driveway. That\'s the problem with this data. While it\'s technically true, it\'s also'

[03:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'completely misleading. And that matters because this data was then packaged into his insurance profile, raised his risk score, and raised his insurance premiums. People don\'t realize that when you bought a car, you\'re paying for it'

[03:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'twice. You\'re paying with it with the money you\'re paying every month for your payments. You\'re paying with it with data. And this data can come back and haunt you. &gt;&gt; None of the data collected just sits on your car. It\'s uploaded, analyzed, and'

[03:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'then tied back directly to you. McKenzie estimates that by 2030, the vehicle data monetization market will be worth over $750 billion. Driving data is recorded, packaged, scored, then sold to insurers.'

[03:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'But who foots that bill? It\'s the driver. &gt;&gt; How much you pay for your car in financing may actually depend on how you drove the car before? &gt;&gt; Insurers are only one part of a much bigger problem. Manufacturers and their'

[03:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'apps can collect data. Data brokers receive it. And law enforcement can request it. And what does an agreement mean when it\'s spread across multiple privacy policies written in jargon that no one can understand and thrown at you when you\'re just trying to connect your'

[04:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'phone to the Bluetooth? This isn\'t meaningful consent. It\'s paperwork disguised as permissions. You are setting up the consumer for failure. You are not really telling them what they\'re writing, what what they\'re agreeing to,'

[04:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'and then you\'re claiming they agree to and that\'s unfair and that\'s deceptive and that\'s punishable by law. When Mosilla investigated these policies, the results were worse than you could imagine. When weighed against other products that people assume are spying on them, cars were the worst. Mosilla'

[04:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'reviewed 25 car brands and said every single one failed its privacy test. Finding most automakers shared data with third parties and 84% sold it. Permission structure is so wide your car'

[04:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'is no longer a private space, but a data source for whoever has access to the account. This is where we need to stop thinking of the car as a toy because the fix isn\'t small. The fix is the whole car. Can you stop your car from spying on you? The easiest place to start is'

[05:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'with your settings. Most cars have privacy controls in the menu. Look for stuff called data sharing, connected services, analytics, diagnostics, location services, personalization, voice assistant, insurance sharing,'

[05:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'driver monitoring. Name changes from manufacturer to manufacturer, but you want to turn off anything sending unnecessary data out of your car. That means there\'s less data leaving your car. But there is a trade-off. Turning off location data can break navigation'

[05:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'and turning off connectivity can disable features like remote unlocking. Car starts to behave more like your phone in flight mode. It still works, but most of the luxury functions you use are unavailable. So, this is the lowest friction step. It gives you more'

[05:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'control, but it won\'t stop everything. When you pair your phone, you\'re giving your car access to everything it holds. You\'re giving it access to your contacts, call logs, messages, calendar, music, and location. So, if you don\'t need to pair your phone, don\'t do it.'

[05:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'The trade-off here is no seamless music, no hands-free, and no perfect integration, but fewer connections means fewer leaks. You can also perform a factory reset. You should do it before you sell your car, or in our case,'

[06:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'before you return the rental. It wipes your personal information and deauthorizes connected accounts. Even if your telephone isn\'t connected, your car has access to the outside world. That\'s Telmatics. Usually, with a built-in SIM card, it lets the car talk to the'

[06:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'manufacturer\'s servers. That\'s how remote unlock works. how the app knows where the car is and how emergency services, diagnostics, and software updates work. Can you remove the SIM card? Sometimes, yes. But for most people, that\'s not your best solution.'

[06:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'It can be difficult to find, buried deep in the car, and it\'ll trigger warning messages, and that\'ll break navigation, radio features, emergency services, and software updates. The more realistic fix is to reduce what that connection is'

[06:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'allowed to share. Disable connected services you don\'t use. Opt out of data sharing where possible. Cancel insurance tracking programs you didn\'t knowingly choose and check the manufacturer\'s privacy portal, not just the car\'s menu,'

[06:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'because some of the controls aren\'t in your car, they\'re in your account. The next thing to check is the cameras. Some cars have cameras outside. Some cars have cameras inside. So, check whether cabin monitoring can be limited. Check'

[07:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'whether camera sharing can be turned off. Now, this doesn\'t mean your car is recording every conversation, but they are often listening for wake words, and they don\'t always get it right. In a car with road noise, music, passengers, and hands-free commands, false triggers can'

[07:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'and do happen. That means your conversations can be recorded without you even realizing it. So, if you\'re not using the voice features, there\'s no reason to leave them listening. So, can you stop your car from spying on you?'

[07:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'Not really. Not without breaking a lot of what makes it a modern car. Because this data collection wasn\'t bolted on as an afterthought. It was designed this way. But you can make it less revealing. You can reduce what it collects. You can'

[07:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'delete what\'s already there. and you can limit who has access. So, you\'ll have to decide how much convenience you\'re willing to sacrifice for control. Because privacy isn\'t about disappearing completely. It\'s about knowing who\'s watching, what data is being collected,'

[07:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'and which doors you can still'
